element_texts.text: sept? 16th Antwerp, a fortified city where we anchored this morning. we weere in the schet? at 8 o'clock landed at unclear at the hotel de st. antoine from whence we went to the cathedral, the museum? or the picture gallery where we saw one of the unclear of which were very pretty. unclear many other places that I do not recollect at present. At the cathedral we saw 2 large pictures by unclear which were taken to paris during the revolution one of which represents the descent from the unclear this is to the right as you face the alter on one of the folding door is represented the salutation of the unclear + the others. the presentry of our infant unclear in the temple this picture is the most celebrated of unclear we went up the tower of this cathedral which has I think 548 steps from which we saw nothing but a perfect map of roads

Wednesday 19
left baloano? at 8 oclock in the morning + at 10 it began raining + did not clear until we arrived at mestre? before which one of the horses in the charriot fell down twice but no one sustained any injury from it though the unclear leg was caught + he was held down until one of others went to his attendance? we reached mestre? at 9 oclock and left it as soon as gondolas could be procured for our large party and the carriages could be attended to for they were left there until we leave this; our two gondolas were rowed by 4? men each, + after I a long round (for it was very wet + disagreeable, which made time unclear more heavily) we were landed safely at the hotel lion blame which is sittuated upon the the canal grande + from which we have a nice view of the old but fine built dings

thursday 20
were all up late this morning breakfasted at 9 oclock + went out in gondolas which we had opened. My aunt, Mrs bathurst her two daughters? + the unclear in one + Mrs. Seyb?, Mary, Brother + I in another. we first went to see the doger? palace where we saw some beautiful pictures by ancient artist the first room salla del maggion consiglio was magnificent so very large. I think 154 feet long + 74 broad. The walls are decorated by some of the paintings above mentioned + the most remarkable are 1st paradise, by unclear which is said to be the largest picture in the world one canvas ^ 174 feet in length is a map of confesion + unclear this is in a measure caused by unclear + time 2nd late? beronese. The pope alexander 3, discover by the doge ziare? + the unclear in the convent of la carita? where he had concealed

himself, when flying from unclear 2nd in 1777. in this chamber are more of the portraits of the doges excepting marino falieri whose portrait is no where to be seen. (the best of the portraits are in a unclear) there is unclear of the ancient continent to be seen which is very curious, there are some very pretty paintings on the ceiling. this room + unclear contain a very extensive library ^ of unclear which the public are allowed to use with permission?. We also saw the lemante chamber which napoleon had repaired for his wife? after taking Venice + then the next room in which the doge's held their private commities? the seats were of red leather cushions. we all sat in the Doges seat thence to the chamber where I? inquisitors held their tribunals. three corners held their thrones or seats on returning we saw a hole which was formerly filled by a lions mouth of marble in which were thrown all the

petitions or complaints which the public wanted to be noticed by the senate there lions mouths were placed in different chambers the stair case ^by which you enter the Doge's palace is very grand + is called the Seala dei giganti. Some say that Marino Falieris head was cut off here + that it bounded to the bottom of the stair case but Marry says it was not in existence at the time. from thence we came to the hotel had dinner + went to see the church Sta. Maria della Salute which was begun in ^ 1632 a thanksgiving after the unclear of the great pestilence, in which 60,000 of the inhabitants are said to have died. There are some beautiful pictures heree. the one which I liked best was the descent of the holy ghost by Titian when he was about 74 years old. There is a most beautiful candelabrum of bronze on the left hand side as you approach it the alter piece is of marble + I think it very pretty - from that we

went to San Giorgio Maggione; this church I did nit like so much. The choir has most beautifully carved backs to the seats of? wood unclear is done by a man by the name of ^ this church was once a unclear of convent 
friday the 21st went to the (academia) academy which has some very pretty pictures indeed in it the first room has a picture of the assumption of/after? the unclear in it by titian?; which looks very fresh indeed + is thought really beautiful in another room was a unclear very pretty picture, also by Titian, of Our Saviour in the temple where his mother + father came back in search of him (the unclear of the Doctors) in the adjoining room was a new picture very pretty painted for the Austrian the subject (the fathers the Doge banishing his son) + the Mother + I think her 2 daughters are trying to

48
this church is very beautiful though not so gaudy as many you see; the tomb of St. Anthony is surrounded by silver & gilted gold lamps which are burning constantly there are also 2 immense candlesticks of silver one weighing 1607, the other 1450, each supported by beautiful marble cherubs they were indeed very pretty by the side of the high altar is a beautiful great candelabrum of bronze executed by Andrea Riccio, ten years of his labour were bestowed there are very pretty ornaments? here also--after to Santa Cristina but it was too dark to see anything; in going there we saw a very pretty public walk surrounded by statues of Generals, bishops etc then to the Hotel--we passed by the beautiful Cafe Pedrocchi--had dinner & very nice rooms. Tuesday--25th--Ferrara--Left Padua during the rain at 8 oclock and arrived at Ferrara at 7 oclock after having been detained first in crossing the Adige, a short time, & then the Po, by which we lost an hour we crossed these rivvers in ferry boats &

49
Hotel St. Inarco--
Wednesday 26th Bologna--Intended leaving Ferrara at 8 oclock but not being able to get post horses we determined to wait until 10 hoping they would arrive, during this time we went to the Library where we saw the tomb of Ariosto & his bust also some of his poetry as well as that of Tapo, it was in their handwriting also the inkstand & armchair of the former both of which looked well worn & particularly the latter, then saw a bible of 14 century printed with a pen & it contained small pictures & one particularly struck the attention of us all it was unclear taking the rib from Adam's side & forming woman the appearance was very singular indeed from thence to a church where I saw nothing of consequence 
then to the Hospital to see the prisons in which Tapo was confined for 7 years & 2 months by Alphonsa Hippolite d'Este some said he was mad & others said not that he was only in love with the sister of A & was imprisoned by A on that account

50
thence to the castle which we only passed through & went to see the small collection of paintings which belong to it there were a few very pretty pictures--then returned to the Hotel & found that horses enough could not be obtained for us all therefore it was thought best that Miss & the maids should set off in the coach as it was the heaviest & was usually behind so off they went thinking that we should overtake them in a short time but to our great vexation & surprise 12 oclock struck, we had taken luncheon & were quite ready to set out yet the horses were wanted but a little before one oclock we were agreeably surprised by Frederic's coming up & telling us that their horses had come & would be put to, in a few minutes so at 1 oclock we were off by our carraige had 4 of the poorest animals to it I ever saw & we went on so slowly that brother Robert got down from his seat cast a unclear & apisted? the postilion to get them on but it was all to very little pur

51
-pose at last we met a postilion coming back who took off 2 of the poor beasts & put his in the place we went faster for a little while then took off another & got to the next post house about three quarters of an hour after the chariot -- we then went on very comfortably & at a very good pace but saw nothing of the coach which had gone on from one post house to another with Miss Seybs telling the Master that the courier was behind with 2 other carriages they also passed the police at the gates of Bologna by Miss Seybs finding one of the men who understood German & to whom she could explain the reason of their being without a passport. When we arrived at the Hotel it was 11 oclock & Miss Seybs had almost given us up it being so late had very comfortable bedrooms & could wish nothing better--

52
Thursday 27 Bologna -- Got up very late & breakfasted at half past 9 -- went to the Academia delle belle Arti which is not very extensive though it is unclear by many to contain the finest collection of paintings in Italy -- those which I thought most of was the Massacre of the Innocents by Guido also these two pictures were most beautiful so very natural many other very pretty ones which it would take too long to mention unclear at this place -- thence to the cathedral where there was nothing worthy of notice; then to St Petronio built in 1132 & repaired in 1390, it is remarkable as being the place in which Charles the 5th emperor of Germany was crowned by Clement 7th it also contains the celebrated Meridian of Capini the gnomon of which is eighty three feet in height
